ray /reɪ/

(rays) 

1. N-COUNT Rays of light are narrow beams of light. 光线 

例： The sun's rays can penetrate water up to 10 feet. 阳光的光线一直能透射到水下10英尺处。 

2.  →  see also X-ray 

3. N-COUNT A ray of hope, comfort, or other positive quality is a small amount of it that you welcome because it makes a bad situation seem less bad. 一丝 (希望、安慰等其他积极因素) 

例： They could provide a ray of hope amid the general economic gloom. 他们能在普遍的经济低迷中带来一丝希望。 

4. V (of an object) to emit (light) in rays or (of light) to issue in the form of rays 发出光束; 闪光 

5. N any of various marine selachian fishes typically having a flattened body, greatly enlarged winglike pectoral fins, gills on the undersurface of the fins, and a long whiplike tail. They constitute the orders Torpediniformes ( electric rays ) and Rajiformes 鳐鱼 

6. N (in tonic sol-fa) the second degree of any major scale; supertonic (首调唱名法的)大音阶的二度; 超音 [music]

